      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Model migration as a response to price changes"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When a provider introduces a cheaper replacement model, migrating workloads is the highest-impact response to a cost-saving opportunity. But migration carries quality and compatibility risks that must be assessed before committing."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Migration decision criteria"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Quality parity: run an evals suite on the new model with the existing prompt to confirm output quality meets the workload's acceptance threshold before migrating production traffic."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "API compatibility: check whether the new model supports all parameters the workload uses (function calling, structured outputs, vision, context length). Incompatibilities require prompt or code changes."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Migration cost: factor in the engineering time for testing and deployment. A 20% cost saving that requires two weeks of engineering is only net positive if the payback period is within the budget year."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Reversibility: ensure the model identifier in the API call can be rolled back in under 30 minutes if the new model causes quality regressions in production."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from dataclasses import dataclass\n\n@dataclass\nclass MigrationROI:\n    monthly_spend_current_usd: float\n    monthly_spend_new_model_usd: float\n    migration_engineering_hours: float\n    engineering_hourly_rate_usd: float = 150.0\n\n    @property\n    def monthly_saving(self) -> float:\n        return self.monthly_spend_current_usd - self.monthly_spend_new_model_usd\n\n    @property\n    def migration_cost(self) -> float:\n        return self.migration_engineering_hours * self.engineering_hourly_rate_usd\n\n    @property\n    def payback_months(self) -> float:\n        if self.monthly_saving <= 0:\n            return float('inf')\n        return self.migration_cost / self.monthly_saving\n\n    def is_worthwhile(self, max_payback_months: float = 6.0) -> bool:\n        return self.payback_months <= max_payback_months\n\n# Example\nroi = MigrationROI(\n    monthly_spend_current_usd=8_000,\n    monthly_spend_new_model_usd=3_500,\n    migration_engineering_hours=20,\n)\nprint(f\"Monthly saving: ${roi.monthly_saving:,.0f}\")\nprint(f\"Payback: {roi.payback_months:.1f} months\")\nprint(f\"Worthwhile? {roi.is_worthwhile()}\")\n# Monthly saving: $4,500 / Payback: 0.7 months / Worthwhile? True\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Building a price change monitoring system"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Manual monitoring of provider pricing pages is error-prone and slow. A lightweight automated monitoring system can detect price changes within hours of publication and trigger the impact assessment workflow automatically."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import hashlib\nimport json\nfrom pathlib import Path\n\nPRICE_CACHE_PATH = Path(\"/var/finops/price-cache.json\")\n\nPROVIDER_RATE_CARDS = {\n    \"anthropic\": {\n        \"claude-sonnet-4\": {\"input\": 3.00, \"output\": 15.00, \"cache_read\": 0.30},\n        \"claude-haiku-4\": {\"input\": 0.80, \"output\": 4.00, \"cache_read\": 0.08},\n    },\n    # Add other providers as needed\n}\n\ndef load_cached_prices() -> dict:\n    if PRICE_CACHE_PATH.exists():\n        return json.loads(PRICE_CACHE_PATH.read_text())\n    return {}\n\ndef save_prices(prices: dict) -> None:\n    PRICE_CACHE_PATH.write_text(json.dumps(prices, indent=2))\n\ndef detect_price_changes(current: dict, cached: dict) -> list[dict]:\n    changes = []\n    for provider, models in current.items():\n        for model_id, prices in models.items():\n            cached_prices = cached.get(provider, {}).get(model_id, {})\n            if prices != cached_prices:\n                changes.append({\n                    \"provider\": provider,\n                    \"model_id\": model_id,\n                    \"old\": cached_prices,\n                    \"new\": prices,\n                })\n    return changes\n\n# Run this as a daily or hourly scheduled job\ndef run_price_monitor():\n    cached = load_cached_prices()\n    changes = detect_price_changes(PROVIDER_RATE_CARDS, cached)\n    if changes:\n        # Notify FinOps team and trigger impact assessment\n        print(f\"PRICE CHANGES DETECTED: {len(changes)} models affected\")\n        for c in changes:\n            print(f\"  {c['provider']}/{c['model_id']}: {c['old']} \u2192 {c['new']}\")\n    save_prices(PROVIDER_RATE_CARDS)\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Common mistakes"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Treating provider price cuts as windfall: a 30% price cut on a model that represents 40% of spend is a material budget surplus. Without an active process to recapture it, the budget just looks underspent and gets cut next cycle \u2014 the saving is lost."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Not tracking the effective date: price changes often have a delayed effective date. Updating the forecast the day of the announcement rather than the effective date introduces a one- to three-month error in timing."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Ignoring the model mix dependency: a price change on Model A does not affect spend on Model B. Computing the portfolio-wide impact requires model-level volume data, not just total token counts."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Conflating list price with effective price: the impact on an organisation with a 30% committed discount is 70% of the list price impact. Always apply existing discounts before computing the budget delta."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Deferring migration decisions until the next annual planning cycle: a new cheaper model available in July that is not evaluated until November represents four months of excess spend."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Key takeaways"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Model price change impact forecasting is a five-step process: detect, assess, model, update forecast, and act."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Compute the cost delta as a step-change in the forecast at the effective date, applied to the affected model's volume only \u2014 not to the entire budget."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Use migration ROI analysis to decide whether a cheaper replacement model is worth the engineering investment, targeting a payback period under 6 months."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Build lightweight automated monitoring of provider rate cards to detect changes within hours rather than days."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Price cuts represent budget surplus that must be actively recaptured \u2014 either through reallocation or formal budget reduction \u2014 not silently absorbed as an underspend."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}